HEADWORD: Schematism
<hw>Sche"ma*tism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>sch⟦eacute⟧matisme</ets> (cf. L. <ets>schematismos</ets> florid
speech), fr. Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ to form. See <er>Scheme</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Astrol.)</fld> <def>Combination of the aspects of
heavenly bodies.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Particular form or disposition of a thing; an
exhibition in outline of any systematic arrangement.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Schematist</ent>⟦br⟧
